Model Building: Forward Stepwise Regression
15
Fitted Model:
Estimated Quality = 4.022 +
0.078*Alcohol +
-0.994*Chlorides +
-0.139*Sulphates +
-1.065*Volatile acidity +
-1.225*Sulphates2 +
0.306*Alcohol * Sulphates
Visual analysis of the residuals for the model suggests that the normality assumption
could be violated. We should be cautious when drawing inferences on the model. The fact
that the quality scores were only given as integer values likely plays a role.

16

Model Analysis: K-Fold Cross Validation
19
●How can we assess our reduced model’s accuracy performance when
compared to using a full model with all explanatory variables?
●K-fold cross validation to split the data into K sets
●Train on K-1 sets, test on the K-th set
●Repeat for all sets
●We use 10 folds, so 90% of the data as training data
Model Analysis: K-Fold Cross Validation
20

MSPE
Reduced Model Full Model
0.4163 0.4176

0.4151 0.4232
Model Analysis: PRESS Statistic
21
●We look at the PRESS statistic of the reduced model as another way to
determine the model’s predictive ability
●If PRESS ≈ SSE, suggests the model is good for prediction
PRESS SSE
669.3189 662.77
MSPE ≅PRESS/n = 0.4186
●Cross Validation suggests that the AIC Model is better than the full
model, and sufficient for prediction on the dataset
Final Notes
22
●This model would be most useful for a winery, who could
use our analysis to decide how to best make wine.
●Worth considering:
○Our modeling methods are built with continuous data in
mind, but the response variable is discrete
○Sulphate level appears to greatly impact wine quality
(main effect, second-order term, and interaction)
